M58.value:
(c) Select whether there is line of sight or not from the drop-down Iist. Consider path control where feasible and reasonable (e.g. acoustic curtains on mobile framing around jumping jack, concrete saw, jack hammer, etc).
Note: Only select 'no' if there is a substantial barrier such as an existing noise barrier, project specific noise barrier (standard measure) or rows of buildings (see Definitions). Blocked line of sight due to vegetation or standard fencing does not count. Furthermore, using path control and/or quieter equipment may help to reduce the mitigation distances for additional mitigation measures.

AV89.value: (b) Enter the shortest distance from source to receiver (i.e. 5 metres) to calculate the noise level at the worst affected receivers to assist with determining the suitable level of mitigation. The LAeq(15minute) noise level at the worst affected receiver 5 metres away is 97 dB(A) from concrete breaking and up to 87 dB(A) during placement of formwork and concrete pour (See below for an example).

M90.value: (b) Enter the shortest distance from source to receiver (i.e. 35 metres) and the rate of production (assumed to be 6 metres per minute) to calculate the noise level at the worst affected receivers to assist with determining the suitable level of mitigation. The highest LAeq(15minute) at the worst affected receiver 35 metres away is 70 dB(A) (from a moving source).
